<DOC><DOCNO> AP891113-0254 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-13-89 1851EST</FILEID><FIRST>u f AM-Kodak-OpticalDisk     11-13 0210</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Kodak-Optical Disk,0215</SECOND><HEAD>Kodak Introduces New High-Capacity Optical Disk</HEAD><DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Eastman Kodak Co. introduced a newoptical computer disk Monday that company officials said is capableof storing 20 percent more information than the largest capacitydisk now on the market.   The 14-inch optical disk will be capable of storing 8.2gigabytes, equivalent to 8,200 megabytes, of information. Each ofthe new disks will be able to hold the equivalent of 48 fullyloaded reels of magnetic tape, the company said.   ``Our competitors _ even with their recent announcements ofincreases in disk capacity _ have not been able to match theperformance or storage capacity of our first generation, 14-inchoptical disks,'' said John Batterton, a general manager of salesand marketing in Kodak's Mass Memory Division. ``We're extendingour lead in the optical storage marketplace.''   Kodak said the new disks would be fully compatible with hardwarecomponents of the Kodak Optical Disk System 6800. The company saidthe system's hardware will be able to write to the new disks, aswell as read from them.   The disks are designed for use by institutions, including banksor hospitals, to store images like X-rays or documents. Each diskis capable of holding 2.7 million typewritten pages.</TEXT></DOC>